04305nam a22006855i 9780271062587DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710625877 a10.1515/97802710625872doi  a(DE-B1597)584266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE99.M6 7aREL0290002bisacsh04a398.2089/9732231 aReid, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFinding Kluskap :bA Journey into Mi'kmaw Myth /cJennifer Reid. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (136 p.) :b3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignifying (on) Scriptures ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Treaties and Aquatic Parasites -- t2 Kluskap and Aboriginal Rights -- t3 The Saint Anne's Day Mission -- t4 Knowing How and Where to Be -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mi'kmaq of eastern Canada were among the first indigenous North Americans to encounter colonial Europeans. As early as the mid-sixteenth century, they were trading with French fishers, and by the mid-seventeenth century, large numbers of Mi'kmaq had converted to Catholicism. Mi'kmaw Catholicism is perhaps best exemplified by the community's regard for the figure of Saint Anne, the grandmother of Jesus. Every year for a week, coinciding with the saint's feast day of July 26, Mi'kmaw peoples from communities throughout Quebec and eastern Canada gather on the small island of Potlotek, off the coast of Nova Scotia. It is, however, far from a conventional Catholic celebration. In fact, it expresses a complex relationship between the Mi'kmaq, Saint Anne, a series of eighteenth-century treaties, and a cultural hero named Kluskap. Finding Kluskap brings together years of historical research and learning among Mi'kmaw peoples on Cape Breton Island, Nova Scotia. The author's long-term relationship with Mi'kmaw friends and colleagues provides a unique vantage point for scholarship, one shaped not only by personal relationships but also by the cultural, intellectual, and historical situations that inform postcolonial peoples. The picture that emerges when Saint Anne, Kluskap, and the mission are considered in concert with one another is one of the sacred life as a site of adjudication for both the meaning and efficacy of religion-and the impact of modern history on contemporary indigenous religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aGluskap (Legendary character). 0aMicmac IndiansxGovernment relations. 0aMicmac IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aMicmac mythology. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271062587zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062587423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271062587/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK